Univariate Analysis

Structure of the dataset

Our data frame consists of 1599 observations with 13 variables. Out of the 13 variables, 12 are input variables, while only one, that is, quality is output varibale.

main feature of interest in the dataset

The main feature of interest in the dataset is the quality of the red wine.

Other features in the dataset that support our investigation

There is only one dependent variable, quality of wine. Therefore, we will try to see how different factors (input variables) affect the quality of wine

Plot is a uniform distribution. Therefore, no transformation is necessary for axis of quality. The plot shows that most number of wines lie in the average range, that is, quality score 5-6. Let’s summarise the quality to look at the maximum and minimum value of quality.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   3.000   5.000   6.000   5.636   6.000   8.000

The minimum is 3 and maximum is 8.

For most wines the pH lies bewtween 3.0 and 3.5 with a spike in exactly the middle.

Let’s move on and explore how different independent variables are correlated with the dependent variable.

##               X fixed.acidity volatile.acidity citric.acid residual.sugar
## [1,] 0.06645261     0.1240516       -0.3905578   0.2263725     0.01373164
##       chlorides free.sulfur.dioxide total.sulfur.dioxide    density
## [1,] -0.1289066         -0.05065606           -0.1851003 -0.1749192
##               pH sulphates   alcohol
## [1,] -0.05773139 0.2513971 0.4761663

From the above correlation table, we see that “fixed.acidity”, “citic.acid”, “residual.sugar”, “sulphates” and “alcohol” are positviely correlated to the quality of wine. This means that as these factors move upward, the quality of wine also increases. On the other hand, “volatile,acidity”, “chlorides”, “free sulfur dioxide”, “total sulfur dioxide”, “density”" and “pH” are negatively correlated to quality. We will explore this further.

In addition to that, the correlation table gives us an idea of how each variable is correlated to quality. And, therefore, I chose to not use the ggpair function to save time.

create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset

We can group “free.sulfur.dioxide” and “total.sulfur.dioxide” together since they both measure the effect of free sulfur dioxide gas on the quality of wine. We create a new variable sulfur_dioxide

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One: Understanding our dataset in terms of the main feature of interest, quality

## <ScaleContinuousPosition>
##  Range:  
##  Limits:    3 --    8

Description One

Plot one gives us a good insight of the dataset. It tells us that most of the wines are of average quality as the quality score lie between 5-7 on a scale of 0-10. It also tells us that the quality scores lie between 3-8. This information can be used to classify good quality wines and poor quality wines.

Plot Two: A boxplot showing how alcohol content influences quality of wine

Description Two

This plot shows that that alcohol content and quality of wine are positively correlated. As the alcohol content increases, which is the median of alcohol content of wines grouped by quality score, the quality of wine also increases. This is confirmed by the Pearson correlation between the two variables which is 0.45. In fact, this is the highest correlation of the quality with any other input variable. Therefore, alcohol content seems to be the most infuential psoitive character.

Plot Three: Check if a thrid variable supports the correlation between alcohol and qaulity and wine

Description Three

This plot is an attempt to understand if the effect of a thrid variable can be included to support the correlation between two varibales. A categorical variable was created by bucketing the variable volatile acidity using quantile methods into four categories “Low”, “Medium”, “High”, “Very-High”. The reason to pick the volatile acidity is because it is negatively correlated to the quality and hence it would be good to have it on the same plot as a positive factor(alcohol). However, the plot we see here is not very good to draw any strong conclusions about the trend. This tells us that the relation is nonlinear. We can only get a basic idea that the quality of wine improves when the volatile acidity goes down. ——

Reflection

Overall, this was an interesting data set to work with. We were ineterested in exploring how different input variables influence the output variable-quality. The first important decision I made that helped with the analyses was to find the Pearson correlation of quality with all other variables. This gave an idea of the factors that are contributing most to the quality of wine. These are, alcohol content, volatile acidity, citric acod content and the sulphates content. The main problem I encountered was I wasn’t able to find a strong linear correlation between the varibales. This can be overcome by using support vector machine model as it the best for small data sets with non linear trends. The prodictive model would greatly enhance the quality of data analysis and I would like to work on it in the future.
